Skip building FA3 (Hopper sm_90 kernels) on Blackwell-only targets.

vllm-flash-attn 2.7.2.post1's `hopper/` source tree uses the old
2-template-arg form of `cutlass::epilogue::collective::detail::
sm90_get_smem_store_op_for_accumulator`. CUTLASS 4.0 added a third
template argument, so the bundled CUTLASS 4.4.2 fails template
deduction for every `*_sm90.cu` instantiation in FA3:

    hopper/epilogue_fwd.hpp(100): error: no instance of function
    template "cutlass::epilogue::collective::detail::
    sm90_get_smem_store_op_for_accumulator" matches the argument list

The vllm-flash-attn cmake gates SASS arch flags via
`cuda_archs_loose_intersection(FA3_ARCHS "9.0a;" "${CUDA_ARCHS}")`
but still compiles the `*_sm90.cu` source files (with `ArchTag_ =
cutlass::arch::Sm90`) when sm_90 isn't in our arch list, which our
sm_120-only build is. Template instantiation runs at host-compile
time regardless of which SASS we'd actually emit, so the .cu files
fail to even compile.

For an sm_120 (Blackwell consumer) build there is nothing to gain
from FA3 — it is a Hopper-only path. FA2 still covers sm_120, so
the simplest fix is to not register the FA3 CMakeExtension at all.

diff --git a/setup.py b/setup.py
index 7c226a7..8e55f3f 100644
--- a/setup.py
+++ b/setup.py
@@ -998,11 +998,10 @@ if _is_hip():

 if _is_cuda():
     ext_modules.append(CMakeExtension(name="vllm.vllm_flash_attn._vllm_fa2_C"))
-    if envs.VLLM_USE_PRECOMPILED or (
-        CUDA_HOME and get_nvcc_cuda_version() >= Version("12.3")
-    ):
-        # FA3 requires CUDA 12.3 or later
-        ext_modules.append(CMakeExtension(name="vllm.vllm_flash_attn._vllm_fa3_C"))
+    # FA3 hopper kernels skipped — this Nix build targets sm_120 (Blackwell
+    # consumer) only; FA3's hopper/ tree is incompatible with the bundled
+    # CUTLASS 4.4.2 anyway (sm90_get_smem_store_op_for_accumulator gained a
+    # third template arg in CUTLASS 4.0).
     # FA4 CuteDSL - Python-only component for FA4's cute DSL support
     # Optional since this doesn't produce a .so file, just copies Python files
     ext_modules.append(
